Images of American living - four centuries of architecture and furniture as cultural expression

Lippincott | 1964 | Eng | Pdf | 498 pag | 106 MB

"From the beginning," writes the author in his preface, "there have been patterns of development in American architecture and furniture that at once grow from and express the fundamental character, aspirations and moods of historic American civilization."

These patterns Alan Gowans traces from the first primitive shelters, medieval in tradition, to the sophisticated structures which mark the period of this nation's emergence into world leadership. Between these twoâ€”one as "functional" as the other â€”are found the varied patterns shaped by diverse peoples and traditions, by the evolving relationship between America and Europe, by social and economic changes
